# Auditor (Python) conventions

Stack: Python 3.12, FastAPI, httpx (async), pydantic v2, clickhouse-connect. Lint with ruff.

## The Finding model is the contract
Everything flows through one pydantic model (define once in `auditor/models.py`):

```python
class Evidence(BaseModel):
    label: str            # "42 GB of DEBUG logs in the last 24h"
    signoz_url: str       # deep link into SigNoz UI — must resolve
class Finding(BaseModel):
    id: str               # "T1", "L2" — matches docs/LEAK-CATALOG.md
    domain: Literal["telemetry", "llm"]
    title: str
    monthly_cost_usd: float          # computed, from real volumes × env rates
    cost_is_estimate: bool = True
    evidence: list[Evidence]         # ≥1 required
    safety_proof: str | None         # e.g. "0 dashboards / 0 alerts reference these metrics"
    fix_ref: str | None              # e.g. "collector/patches/T2-orphan-metrics.yaml"
    status: Literal["detected", "fix_ready", "applied", "verified", "failed"]
    verification: dict | None        # before/after numbers
```

## Detector pattern
- One module per leak type in `telemetry_auditor/` or `llm_auditor/`, each exposing
  `async def detect(ctx) -> list[Finding]`. The orchestrator in `main.py` gathers them.
- ClickHouse: parameterized queries only; introspect table names once at startup and cache
  them in `ctx`; if a table is missing, return a Finding-less warning, don't crash the run.
- SigNoz API: confirmed routes live as constants in `signoz_api.py` with a comment noting the
  SigNoz version they were verified against.

## LLM usage inside the auditor
- LLM is used for ranking/explanation text and OTTL config drafting — never for the numbers.
  Volumes, counts, and costs come from queries.
- temperature=0, request JSON output, validate with pydantic, retry once on parse failure.
- Log model, input/output tokens per call (we display our own agent cost in the UI).

## Service behavior
- Endpoints: `GET /findings`, `POST /audit`, `POST /apply/{id}`, `POST /verify/{id}`,
  `GET /events` (SSE stream of status changes).
- Never block the event loop; ClickHouse sync calls go through a thread executor.
- Errors return `{error, hint}` with a concrete next step ("check SIGNOZ_API_KEY", not "failed").
- No unit-test suite required (hackathon), but each detector gets a `python -m` smoke entry
  that prints its findings as a table.
